{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/from-the-bridge-to-tasks-planning-build-gannt-chart-in-python-r-and-tableau-7256fb7615f8", "time": 1683007038.057617, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/from-the-bridge-to-tasks-planning-build-gannt-chart-in-python-r-and-tableau-7256fb7615f8/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "From the bridge to tasks planning: build Gannt chart in Python, R, and Tableau | by Pavlo Horbonos | Towards Data Science", "h1": "From the bridge to tasks planning: build Gannt chart in Python, R, and Tableau", "description": "Some time ago I have got an idea, that there is a lot of information about bar charts, histograms, scatterplots, line charts and other effective but very simple and ordinary instruments for data\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gantt_chart#CITEREFWeaver2012a", "anchor_text": "Gantt chart", "paragraph_index": 1}, {"url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_Gantt", "anchor_text": "Henry Gantt", "paragraph_index": 2}, {"url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Hermann_Sch%C3%BCrch&action=edit&redlink=1", "anchor_text": "Hermann Sch\u00fcrch", "paragraph_index": 2}, {"url": "https://archive.org/details/cu31924004570853/page/n5/mode/2up", "anchor_text": "\u201cThe Gantt chart, a working tool of management\u201d", "paragraph_index": 3}, {"url": "https://www.mosaicprojects.com.au/PDF_Papers/P158_Henry_L_Gantt.pdf", "anchor_text": "\u201cHenry L. Gantt, 1861\u20131919. A retrospective view of his work\u201d", "paragraph_index": 3}, {"url": "https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/plotrix/plotrix.pdf", "anchor_text": "plotrix", "paragraph_index": 9}, {"url": "https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/plotrix/plotrix.pdf", "anchor_text": "package", "paragraph_index": 9}, {"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/can-python-dataviz-libraries-repeat-the-tableau-worksheet-e38ef2876f04", "anchor_text": "already compared Tableau", "paragraph_index": 11}, {"url": "https://twitter.com/MidvelCorp", "anchor_text": "https://twitter.com/MidvelCorp", "paragraph_index": 17}, {"url": "https://blaize.tech/", "anchor_text": "https://blaize.tech/", "paragraph_index": 17}], "all_paragraphs": ["Some time ago I have got an idea, that there is a lot of information about bar charts, histograms, scatterplots, line charts and other effective but very simple and ordinary instruments for data visualization. Even more, I can assume, that the knowledge of how to build these common charts have to be treated as basic and mandatory for every Data Scientist or DataViz specialist. But a whole variety of plots and visualization exist. They are less common and more specific but surely should be in your inventory. Even more, you also have to be familiar with some modern instruments for such charts creation. That\u2019s how I came with the idea of \u201cEpic Charts\u201d series, and you are looking at the first issue of it.", "The first issue of my \u201cEpic Charts\u201d series is dedicated to the Gantt chart. It is a en xample of schedule visualization. Its classical implementation shows the periods of tasks within the project: horizontal lines contain the tasks (or phases) and vertical lines contain dates or time ranges or even simple periods counts. So, each task is shown as a fixed-length bar, which occupies some timeline (or several ones). The modern version also may include additional data about urgency, the relation between phases, and transitions between the phases.", "Firstly created in 1896 by Karol Adamiecki, this chart was described in detail by Henry Gantt in his work \u201cWork Wages and Profits\u201d, which also contained his earlier publications. The first application of the Gantt chart together with its visualization appeared in 1912 in Hermann Sch\u00fcrch\u2019s publication. Actually, it is a chart from the cover. Gannt developed several variations of schedule graphs (see one below, for example), but Sch\u00fcrch has given them the form which we have been using till today.", "You can find more information in the sources of that time \u2014 \u201cThe Gantt chart, a working tool of management\u201d (1922), and in modern researches \u2014 \u201cHenry L. Gantt, 1861\u20131919. A retrospective view of his work\u201d (2012). That\u2019s enough for historical facts, let\u2019s go to the implementation.", "We will work with the test example I have created. It simple project imitation with a few phases, some simultaneous tasks, and some repeatable tasks.", "We will start with the all-known matplotlib library. As it is the basic which every Data Scientist knows, it needs no presentation. So, a bit dates manipulations and the plot is ready:", "In another example, we will use Plotly library \u2014 another famous package. It has a powerful engine for interactive visualizations and a lot of built-in charts type. Including Gantt one!", "R community produced numerous plotting libraries, including some with interactive charts. Of course, they differ in visualization style, in interactivity, and in the syntax of plot parameters, but chart principles leave the same. And since there is no matter of which library to choose, I will create two examples.", "Firstly I will produce a Gantt plot with pure ggplot2, the most famous library. We will use the same data, make some preparation, and here it is:", "The second example uses plotrix package \u2014 one of the independent plotting libraries. Since it aggregates a lot of functionality, code is shorter and the result is \u201cprettier\u201d.", "Of course, you are free to choose any other library.", "I have already compared Tableau and custom plotting with Python. And I have found Tableau as a very pleasant tool for beautiful visualizations. Its inventory is large, you can generate almost any type of chart. Including the Gantt chart!", "And the algorithm is very simple:", "And voila \u2014 the chart is ready:", "That\u2019s all for today. Stay tuned for the next issues of \u201cEpic Charts\u201d. And, as always in my articles, you may find working examples on my GitHub:", "Also make sure you didn\u2019t miss my article about recreation Tableau visualizations with Python:", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Art & Code | https://twitter.com/MidvelCorp \ud83d\udcbb| Head of Blockchain Security in https://blaize.tech/ | web3 and blockchain enthusiast and researcher"], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F7256fb7615f8&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Ffrom-the-bridge-to-tasks-planning-build-gannt-chart-in-python-r-and-tableau-7256fb7615f8&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Ffrom-the-bridge-to-tasks-planning-build-gannt-chart-in-python-r-and-tableau-7256fb7615f8&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fnew-story&source=---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------new_post_sidenav-----------", "anchor_text": "Write"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/search?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Ffrom-the-bridge-to-tasks-planning-build-gannt-chart-in-python-r-and-tableau-7256fb7615f8&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav---------